notes.note: PREREQ: CHEMISTRY 2080 OR EQUIVALENT. RECOMMENDED: ANSC 1100, 1150. IF LAB SECTIONS ARE FULL SEE PROFESSOR. Introduction to animal nutrition, including digestive physiology and metabolism of domestic animals and other species

NATURAL HISTORY/CARE/MGMT/HEALTH AND BREEDING OF EXOTIC AVIAN SPECIES W/EMPHASIS ON PSITTACINES (PARROTS & RELATED SPECIES) & RAPTORS (BIRDS OF PREY). LECTURES, DEMONSTRATIONS AND OPTIONAL FIELD TRIPS. IF FULL SEE PROFESSOR. Students may not add ANSC 2150 after the second lecture period.

THIS COURSE PREREQUISITE FOR ANSC 2510,3510,3540,3550. IF FULL, SEE INSTRUCTOR. Introduction to background and scientific principles relating to dairy cattle production. Labs provide understanding of dairy cattle production.
PREREQUISITES: ANSC 1100 AND ANSC 1160 OR PERMISSION OF INSTRUCTOR. IF FULL SEE INSTRUCTOR. Course provided basics of equine biology, form, function, care management and handling, with hands-on labs.
Animal specific and general areas of welfare discussed for farm and companion animals.

AN SC 2500 or permission of instructor. Application of scientific principles to practical herd management with emphasis on herd health and animal well-being. Lab emphasizes practical applications of herd management.
Prerequisite: 1 yr Intro biology, ANSC 1100 or equivalent intro physiology course. Introduces features and applications of various animal models for biomedical research on human health and diseases.

course.subject: ANSC
course.course_title: Molecular and Cellular Approaches to Reproductive Physiology

notes.note: Prereq: 1 year of intro biology and intro physiology (ANSC 1100, 2400, or BIOAP 3110) or equivalent. Lectures on selected topics in reproductive biology of mammals focusing on how research questions are formulated, addressed and influenced by previous discoveries. Labs focus on cellular and molecular methods to study reproduction.

PREREQUISITES: AN SC 1100 & 2120 OR EQUIVALENT;ANSC 3550 ENCOURAGED. DESIGNED FOR JUNIORS, SENIORS AND ENTERING GRADUATE STUDENTS. IF FULL SEE PROFESSOR. Integrates concepts of cattle nutrition and farm nutritional management to help students understand and appreciate factors influencing the performance of cattle under diverse conditions. Herd case studies are used and there are field trips to local farms.
Physiology and regulation of endocrine secretions. Emphasizes neuroendocrine, reproductive, growth, and metabolic aspects of endocrinology. Examples are selected from many animals, including humans.
Enrollment in Dairy Fellows. Emphasizes dairy herd business management with application to herd management analysis. Laboratory includes farm tours and analysis.

course.subject: ANSC
course.course_title: Quantitative Decision Making on Dairy Farms

notes.note: Prerequisite: ANSC 2500

PREREQUISITES: AN SC 4570 OR PERMISSION OF INSTRUCTOR. 2nd course of a 2-sequence program that will further develop students' skills to be able to communicate in Spanish higher-level dairy production tasks and principles to Hispanic dairy workers.

Merchandizing of replacement beef heifers: budgeting, advertising, animal preparation, cataloging, clerking and reporting. Hands on experience by conducting a sale of beef heifers from the Empire Heifer Development Program.
Prerequisites: ANSC 2400.

ON-THE-JOB LEARNING EXPERIENCE UNDER SUPERVISION OF QUALIFIED PROFESSIONALS. INTERNSHIPS MUST BE APPROVED IN ADVANCE BY STUDENT ADVISOR. REGISTER WITH INDEPENDENT STUDY FORM (AVAILABLE IN 140 ROBERTS HALL).

Prerequisite: permission of instructor. Students must register using independent study form (available in 140 Roberts Hall). S-U or letter grades. May include individual tutorial study or a lecture topic selected by a professor. Because topics may change, the course may be repeated for credit.
Prerequisite: GPA of at least 2.7. Students must register using independent study form (available in 140 Roberts Hall).

Prerequisite: junior or senior standing; GPA of at least 2.7. Not open to students who have earned 6 or more undergraduate research credits elsewhere in the college. Students must register using independent study form (available in 140 Roberts Hall). Affords opportunities for students to carry out independent research under appropriate supervision. Anyone interested in undergraduate research should ask their advisor about opportunities.

course.course_title: Undergraduate Honors Research in Animal Science

notes.note: Prerequisite: permission of instructor. Students must register using an Independent Study Form (available in 140 Roberts Hall).
